 England","Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Blakeland, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","St Mary the Virgin Churchyard, Calne, Wiltshire Unitary Authority, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Blakeland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Lawkland (WR Yorks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Lackland","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Durham): topographic name from Lawkland in Yorkshire. The placename derives from Old Norse <i>laukr</i> ‘leek’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":17,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert de Blakeland V was born in 1242, in Calne, Wiltshire, England, his father, Sir Richard de Blakeland IV, was 42 and his mother, Beatrice Stuteville, was 27. He married Lady Agnes Buckland in 1259, in Calne, Wiltshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1286, in his hometown, at the age of 44, and was buried in Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1242–1286":"1242–1286","1242–1303":"1242–1303","1265–1286":"1265–1286","1200–1245":"1200–1245","1215–1303":"1215–1303","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","Aft 1245":"pärast 1245","1265":"1265","1242":"1242","1286":"1286","about 1240":"umbes 1240","Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Calne, Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","Blakeland, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","St Mary the Virgin Churchyard, Calne, Wiltshire Unitary Authority, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1242–1286":"1242–1286","1242–1303":"1242–1303","1265–1286":"1265–1286","1200–12